<!--
	sec-surface-integrals.ptx
	Section 3: Surface Integrals, Stokes', and the Divergence Theorem.

	A section is a container; each class meeting gets its own
	<worksheet> file, which we pull in with <xi:include/>.  This
	keeps individual worksheets small enough to edit comfortably
	and lets you re-order class meetings by re-ordering includes.
-->
<section xml:id="sec-surface-integrals"
		 xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

	<title>Surface Integrals, Stokes', and the Divergence Theorem</title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Line integrals measured a field along a curve; now we measure a
			field across a <em>surface</em>. Parametrizing a surface with two
			parameters gives us tangent vectors, a normal vector, a way to
			compute <term>surface area</term>, and the <term>flux</term> of a
			vector field through the surface. These surface integrals are the
			setting for the last two great theorems of the course:
			<term>Stokes' Theorem</term>, which lifts Green's circulation form
			to surfaces in space, and the <term>Divergence Theorem</term>,
			which ties the flux out of a closed surface to the divergence
			inside it.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<!-- Class meeting 12: Parametrized surfaces and surface integrals -->
